Strategies to achieve the Vision are to:

- Complete the right task, the right way, every time;

- Improve process safety to prevent LOC events;

- Improve workforce fluency in process safety; and

- Ensure the workforce has the right skills and competencies.



The Refinery's metrics and targets are communicated and updated to employees on a routine basis. They are reviewed during team meetings, through the Refinery's web page, business plan roll-out meetings, and management communications. The Refinery metrics include leading indicators. Leading indicators drive performance in a way that will prevent PSM/RMP incidents. Senior management and employees are held accountable for meeting the Refinery's metric targets. 



The Refinery externally reports the following metrics:

- Number of LOC Tier 1 Tier 2 incidents (as defined in API Recommended Practice 754, Process Safety Performance Indicators for the Refining and Petrochemical Industries);

- Number of overdue Action items from API Tier 1 and Tier 2 incident investigations;

- Number of overdue Vessel and Piping inspections; and

- Number of overdue PHA recommendations.



Continuous Management Commitment

Managers focus on continual improvement of program prevention elements. They prioritize plans to focus on the highest impact items in alignment with the Refinery's vision and objectives discussed above. Managers must: 

- Understand potential risks;

- Understand requirements;

- Assess and audit for effectiveness;

- Prioritize gaps;

- Provide resources including subject matter experts;

- Direct implementation;

- Review progress against plans; and

- Verify compliance.



Planning and Organizing

Each prevention program element is assigned to a Refinery manager who has the overall accountability. 



Implementing

Refinery personnel are provided with initial training on applicable process safety procedures. Refr

esher training is provided on an as-needed basis. Training is conducted following any changes to the process safety procedures.  Findings from investigations, PHAs or other processes are communicated to the appropriate personnel in various ways, which may include e-mails, bulletins, training requiring sign off, or the Refinery intranet.



Controlling

Management and the subject matter experts responsible for each prevention program element periodically conduct internal reviews or audits against the goals and objectives of the element. The procedures are reviewed, revised, and approved to ensure that they remain accurate and reflect the current practices.



Verifying and Improving

Refinery senior management verifies and improves its programs through:

- Assessments;

- Field audits of high-risk process safety activities;

- Field verification and validation of audit findings and PHA recommendations;

- Field audits of completed solutions from loss and near-loss investigations;

- Reviews of significant process safety incidents to ensure the quality of investigations and implementation of appropriate solutions to prevent reoccurrence;

- Participation in joint management-employee committees on health, personal safety and process safety so that representatives from organizations throughout the Refinery have an opportunity to communicate their safety concerns and discuss progress on critical safety initiatives;

- Review of process safety, personal safety and environmental metrics to set targets and identify improvement opportunities; and

- Review of progress on action items from audits and safety meetings. Review is primarily tracked in databases, dashboards or in meeting minutes.



Necessary expertise to support the Refinery's work processes is provided through dedicated organizations such as Technical, Maintenance and Reliability, Health Environment and Safety and Process Safety. These groups possess a combination of technical training and practical hands-on exp

erience which is necessary to not only solve problems and implement solutions, but to effectively communicate and enforce the need to implement the various prevention program elements. When a special situation requires outside expertise, necessary resources are assembled from other CUSA refineries, operating companies, or contract specialists.



2. Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps 

